UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1949
1 A RESOLUTION honoring the YMCA on the organization's 175th anniversary in
2 the United States.
3 WHEREAS, the Young Men's Christian Association (YMCA) marks its 175th
4 anniversary in the United States in 2026, having been founded this country by Thomas
5 Valentine Sullivan at the Old South Church in Boston, Massachusetts, on December 29,
6 1851; and
7 WHEREAS, inspired by the YMCA movement in England, the organization has
8 carried on the mission to put Christian principles into practice by building healthy spirit,
9 mind, and body for all; and
10 WHEREAS, the YMCA has continually adapted to meet the evolving needs of
11 American communities, strengthening society by bringing people together, fostering
12 relationships, and creating a sense of belonging; and
13 WHEREAS, the YMCA's legacy includes providing safe housing during the
14 industrial revolution, pioneering the first night school and English as a second language
15 classes, inventing basketball, and providing the first group swim lessons; and
16 WHEREAS, the YMCA served as the birthplace of Father's Day, with the first
17 celebration held at the YMCA in Spokane, Washington, in 1910; established the Youth
18 and Government Program in 1936, a premier civic engagement initiative that continues
19 today; and led humanitarian efforts during wartime, including the work of John R. Mott,
20 YMCA leader and President Woodrow Wilson's general secretary for the National War
21 Work Council, who received the Nobel Peace Prize in 1946 for undertaking such efforts;
22 and
23 WHEREAS, the YMCA has become the nation's leading nonprofit provider of child
24 care and afterschool programs since the 1970s and 1980s to support working families, has
25 served as the leading provider of emergency child care for frontline workers, and was a
26 significant provider of food during the coronavirus pandemic; and
27 WHEREAS, today, nearly 2,600 YMCAs serve more than 10,000 communities
Page 1 of 2
